	doi = {10.2307/3983680},
	abstract = {The importance of understanding the causes of tropical deforestation hardly needs emphasizing as the 1990s begin. However, a major difficulty researchers in all fields face is that time paths of forest cover change in tropical areas are poorly understood. Despite path-breaking volumes by John Richards and Richard Tucker, the history of the decline of tropical forests is still largely unknown. This article looks as closely as the data permits at the history of forest cover in the Philippines. It will briefly review data sources and forest types, and discuss the pre- and post-1950 history of forest cover. The history of forest decline in the post-1950 period will then provide the basis for the calculation of deforestation rates from 1950 to 1987. The quantity, quality, and comparability of available forest cover data are usually less than what social scientists would desire. Since this situation is unlikely to change for the better in the near future, the best a researcher can do is to use creativity (carefully) in gathering data from a variety of sources, state as clearly as possible the strengths and weak- nesses of each data set, and on the basis of the first two steps, present a well-reasoned argument that captures the major elements of the process under discussion. The researcher encounters severe problems with data when attempting to reconstruct the decline of twentieth-century Philippine forest cover. However, there is enough information to analyze a general outline of Philippine forest cover decline.},
